If I remember correctly, at least in Texas this law came into being when
credit cards primarily meant the cards issued by the gas companies and
the department stores. It was looked upon as a way to avoid usury laws
to allow a company to charge extra for the use of a credit card, either
by a direct fee or indirectly by a cash discount. This didn't come up
in Texas for decades, then when the gas stations tried to give discounts
for cash back in the 80's someone at the state attorney general's office
noticed that this was illegal in Texas, and started sending out
threatening letters, which quickly stopped the process. The law doesn't
really make sense in the days of third-party credit card companies like
MasterCard and Visa, but it is a popular law among credit card users and
credit card companies alike, so its chances of being changed are next to
nothing.

