Yes, Ronnie, the ONLY reason. My vast majority of my sales come in one
of two ways, either through my booth, or through eBay. If they come
through my booth, there is a record of the transaction maintained by the
mall, and I receive my money by check from the mall owner. No real way
I could cheat on my taxes if I wanted to. The only advantage I have is
the very small fee the mall charges me on check transactions which is
their fee to the check guarantee service.

If the sale comes through eBay, it is either paid for by check or by
money order, and either way the money goes into the bank, and would be
easily tracable. Cashing the money orders at the post office and then
claiming a lower sales price would be the easiest thing in the world to
raise the suspicions of an auditor, and the records of eBay could
probably be checked if the IRS wanted to push the matter. Having a
smaller profit margin on those transactions where the mode of payment is
postal money order is a dead give-away. Not to say some people don't do
it, but they are taking a very substantial risk.

On the few transactions that are handled outside of eBay and outside of
the mall, again, what do you think an auditor would think if all of your
transactions done in this manner suddenly had a dramatically lower
profit margin than those done through the mall or through eBay?

If I ran my own shop independent of a mall, I like to think would choose
to act in an ethical manner, but as it is the choice is essentially made
for me due to the way my business is transacted, I guess we'll never
know.

